28/11/2006
Pope Benedict XVI met with Turkish political leaders, including President Ahmet Necdet Sezer and Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan, as well as key Muslim religious figures in Ankara on Tuesday (November 28th).
The pope then headed to Istanbul to meet with the spiritual leader of the world's Orthodox Christians, Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew I.
Czech Republic President Vaclav Klaus met with Greek Prime Minister Costas Karamanlis and Parliament Speaker Anna Psarouda-Benaki in Athens on Thursday (November 23rd).
Talks focused on EU-related issues and bilateral relations.
Bulgarian Prime Minister Sergey Stanishev wrapped up a four-day visit to China on Wednesday (November 22nd).
He held talks with senior officials and sealed a total of four bilateral co-operation accords.
Stanishev then travelled to Hanoi, where he met with Vietnamese counterpart Nguyen Tan Dung.
NATO Secretary General Jaap de Hoop Scheffer met with Serbian Foreign Minister Vuk Draskovic in Brussels on Thursday (November 23rd).
De Hoop Scheffer said NATO expects the right signals from Serbia before deciding on any closer integration with the Alliance.
Macedonian Prime Minister Nikola Gruevski met with Hungarian counterpart Ferenc Gyurcsany on Thursday (November 23rd).
Gyurcsany said Macedonia's goal of joining NATO in 2008 is realistic.
Bulgarian Interior Minister Rumen Petkov met with Libyan leader Muammar Qaddafi in Tripoli on Wednesday (November 22nd).
Petkov also visited the five Bulgarian nurses being detained on charges of infecting hundreds of children with HIV.
(Various sources -- 21/11/06 - 28/11/06)
